V Need for Speed: Escape takes place in America.
Overview
What should have been a carefree walk had become a routine morning trip to work due to a series of completely inappropriate and careless errors.
The ambitions were to some extent satisfied, but it did not matter, since no one clearly wanted to do the extra work.
Before leaving the new version with the subtitle "The Escape", there was great hope.
It was expected that it would move the previous series of Need For Speed in a new direction; demonstration versions showed that the game would take a decent place in the genre of racing games.
We were curious to see parts of the game, where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with the NFS, a lot differs from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the overall impression is that several unnecessary mistakes have been made in this series of games for several years.
So it's not really a mistake, it's an inexplicable line of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You're part of a story whose main character, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by engaging in an illegal race across America.
You're sitting in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
A few interesting features are involved.
The route consists of 10 stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race runs on its own route, each stage takes place in a diverse and interesting environment.
There is therefore no feeling that the game is always the same.
Although the schedule is at the same level as in previous parts of the series, some routes are pleasant to look at.
Still, the game does not produce strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs, or high in the snowy mountains is very pleasant.
In addition, the race brings back to life an unusual detail from time to time.
For example, in the desert you fall into a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you need to be careful not to fall under the avalanche.
The individual races are pretty well arranged.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while, you try to get a few competitors (in fact, a regular race); then you try to improve the time (a standard race with a timer); or you compete with one opponent.
Among other things, you come across the police from time to time, which makes your task even more difficult.
The components on the outside of the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation, where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him, pushing the buttons at the right time.
It's nothing complicated.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much less than you could have expected (only three to be exact).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for the game because it's not enough; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more interesting.
The racing model follows previous models.
This means that it no longer represents something special, but it cannot be considered a flaw.
If you're looking for real life simulations, you're going to have to look elsewhere.
Still, this driving model is very good for dynamic racing, although there are better options in the market.
So far, so good.
But after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driver's model, the collision model isn't so good.
You don't expect that kind of game to change and clash, but if you don't have any idea how your car's gonna behave, something's not.
Usually, running or driving past a car in a dense stream, you sometimes touch the other car a little bit, but sometimes in almost the same situation your car starts to creak.
Or the intrusions were broken.
It's not that important because of the restart system, but it's enough to spoil the fun.
The restarts are arranged so that if you crash or leave the route far away, the game will bring you back to the point where it crashed.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start a race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work out, but you can't quite rely on it.
Sometimes the restarts are not enough, and you have to learn at least a part of the race.
An important lack of play is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done in a certain way, or you just won't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian vehicles at a certain location in the same configuration, regardless of whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying when you see your opponent easily drive between two cars moving in the opposite direction, while when you are driving there, the cars are already located in such a way that you either need to drive them around or drop the speed.
It doesn't matter when you get close to them; it's all arranged so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game you find several places where, regardless of time, the same rival overtakes you in the same place.
This is especially obvious at the end of the game, on the long bridge where you are heading in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your rival must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's coming to you, he's making it worse for you to review, which leads to one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand trying to make the game more interesting and full of adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's starting to get more and more irritable.
Too bad, because despite the simple model of driving, the game is busy and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what you don't miss -- a concept with fifty unique routes, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during the race is unusual.
You need to track the charges along the way, because it is on them that your car may change, even though in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Machines are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are for direct cuts of the highway; and exotic super-sports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain routes.
The main mode of story mode is closely connected to the mode challenge mode; these are the races on individual plots that you will learn on the course of the game.
Here you win for your personal business both medals and glasses, common to challengees and stories regimes.
Many opportunities are available for higher driving levels: starting with cars and ending with profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the Autolog online function, which, among other things, compares your results with that of other players and provides communication with the public.
Here is another flaw that is difficult to understand; this is an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car fall into the tunnel of the subway, where you race in the dark.
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let's say it is) when suddenly a subway train runs into your rear, turning your car into a scrap metal chest.
For several days, our editors discussed whether no one really thought for a second at the time of the game, or whether its creators really think we are such morons.
The technical component of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression of the video is most pleasant, sometimes even shocking.
Although in some critical moments the quality of the recording is sometimes quite low.
This is especially true of incidents involving a large number of participants, where a good record would not be particularly helpful to you.
The sound's fine; the soundtrack is on the lover.
To please the widest possible youth audience, the soundtrack 'entered compositions of different styles'; but few people will buy the game because of its music.
Overall impression of Need for Speed: The escape is pretty messy.
If the game were to avoid clearly unnecessary errors, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of the NFS over the past few years.
In any case, the game leaves a sense of inadequacy.
Of course it's a good time, but get ready to see the flaws blind you like an airport spotlight.
