Changes in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourist agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourism.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, tourist agencies at that time mostly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists drove to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crime in the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both Black Sea countries); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, resulting in significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A major paradox of the socialist period was that socialist citizens (i.e. and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakian citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; otherwise, it was not possible to travel individually.
At the time, travel agencies were offering trips to the West, but it was either standing in line all night, sleeping bag, or having "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
A currency permit was needed for travel to the West, and it was not granted to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not freely converted; it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West without a currency permit.
Most of the time, Czechs spent their vacations at home, which resulted in a large number of cottages and summer homes, this habit persists today.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus survived the real revolution.
Whereas until 1989, GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, Czechs had spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox, which we are no longer aware of, is that until 1989 we were unable to freely visit Croatia's most popular now, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, and this marked the beginning of a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't get enough to travel to the west, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was short of a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was its desire to bring its own food (conservations, salamis, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely converted Czech crown, and decades later our tourists can finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income grew, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourism agencies to prepare regular charter flights, and compared to the past, airlines have now become incredibly cheap because of the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit virtually all the developed world countries except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of the post-revolution journeys occurred in 2000, leading to the historic first direct charter voyage from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been carried by Czech tourists to the warm exotic countries, leaving the Czech Republic through twelve exotic routes in winter.
About 100,000 Czechs now visit exotic countries every year!
And another important development of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, and my country has thus become the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in 2008 Czechs spent more than half of their leave abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person while travelling abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
