UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, developed a polymer modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality, environmentally sound and temperature-resistant.
If traffic signals were to be addressed, it would be necessary to repair some 200,000 dams for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Naher, a UNAM chemical researcher, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of asphalted road surfaces is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or reduced to zero.
His lecture on the technological view of pits read in the International Year of Chemistry said that the laboratory for which he was responsible was developing a polymer modified bitumen for producing a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Naher said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, like in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus to resist the formation of caves.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of oil, is the sequence of hydrocarbons molecules, some of which are the high molecular mass called asphalt, and others are the low molecular mass referred to as molecules, which together give the road covering its characteristic viscous behaviour.
The marital behaviour of bitumen is the fact that it behaves like liquid at high temperatures of about 180 degrees, at 120 °C, and at 50 °C, it retains almost a solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance to street asphalt is not permanent, but changes during the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, said the chemical engineering specialist.
The scientist observed that the streets of Mexico were largely covered with flexible coatings, made up of six layers of material, three of which included bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen made of small stones left in bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that was made up of this coating, he said, was buried in a bitumen.
When driving vehicles and exerting effort, this helps the forces to distribute very well on the road.
If it were modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt floor, he added, the last layer, which is called a layer of wear made from a small stone, is actually sand immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the wheels of transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt coating and road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these efforts, the layer of wear also requires adequate thickness, and the material from which it is made should be taken into account.
The weather, especially the humidity and temperature dropovers, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said because it has a significant impact on asphalt.
When the earth is wet, the water penetrates the surface and is difficult to get out of, this causes all the layers of the roof to grow soft and therefore the formation of the caves.
In the formation of the pits, he said that the first one was a layer of wear, and only then did it affect the bitumen, but the damage did not take place immediately, which should be considered in the first signs of ongoing repair programmes.
A member of the National Research System explained that the transport burden is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each surface layer must always be linked to the transport load and it is necessary to ensure that this requirement is met in order to prevent frequent pits.
Rafael Herrera said that there was still much to be done about bitumen, such as bitumen emulsions that are already on the market in other countries and even help to make pits easily and without high temperatures.
