Introduction of the “Golden Rule” of the budget into the Constitution
The leadership of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in Austria decided on Tuesday to write a budget “golden rule” into the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid possible declines in Austria's credit rating agencies (three A).
Chancellor of Social Democrat Werner Faimann personally announced the decision at the end of the meeting of the Council of Ministers, with the Austrian State debt being 74.6 per cent, much higher than the upper threshold of the rule of 60% established by the Maastricht Treaty but lower than the government debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria's capacity to pay fell by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay a percentage of three thousand euros more each year, the Deputy Chancellor and Minister for Foreign Affairs of Christian Democrats, Michael Spindelegger, cited.
Austria therefore fulfils the Eurozone Summit requirement on 26 October in Brussels; Heads of State and Government have demanded a reduction in budgetary deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The ruling adopted by the Austrian Government resembles the German model, since Germany was the first European country to adopt the “rule”.
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the State budget should be reduced by 0.75 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and from 2017, the structural deficit of the federal State budget should not exceed 0.35 per cent of GDP, and land, like municipalities, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to make the public debt go down below the 60 per cent mark of the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
